               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18481023-2445-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2445-18481023 t18481023-2445-offence-1 t18481023-2445-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2445. <persName id="def1-2445-18481023" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2445-18481023" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2445-18481023" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2445-18481023" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ELIZA DAVIS</hi>, <hi rend="italic">alias<rs id="t18481023-alias-1" type="alias">
                           <join result="nameAlias" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2445-18481023 t18481023-alias-1"></join> Jane King</rs>
                     </hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18481023-2445-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18481023-2445-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18481023-2445-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>, uttering counterfeit coin, after a previous conviction.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1191" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1191" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1191" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1191" type="given" value="CALEB EDWARD"></interp>CALEB EDWARD POWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant-solicitor to the Mint. I pro<lb></lb>duce a copy of the record of Eliza Davis's conviction at this Court, in March, 1847—I have examined it with the original, it is a true copy (<hi rend="italic">read</hi>).</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1192" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1192" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1192" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1192" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LEE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, N</hi> 179). I was present when the prisoner was tried in March, 1847—she is the person.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1193" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1193" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1193" type="surname" value="PRIDLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1193" type="given" value="JOHANNA"></interp>JOHANNA PRIDLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and am a cheesemonger at Dock-bead. On Saturday, 16th Sept., between eight and nine in the evening, the prisoner came to my house for a quarter of a pound of butter, and gave me a five-shilling piece—I took twopence-halfpenny, and gave her the change—I did not look at the crown, but threw it into the till—there was another crown there—I took no notice what sort of a crown it was—I afterwards took out two crowns; one was a new Victoria one, and my daughter said, "I took that"—the other was an old one—there were none but those two in the till—I can swear the prisoner is the person—I took particular notice of her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1194" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1194" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1194" type="surname" value="PRIDLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1194" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN PRIDLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am daughter of the last witness. On 16th Sept. I received a crown-piece in payment of a bill—it was a Victoria crown—I generally observe the reign of money when I take it—it looked new and bright—I put it into the till—not many minutes after, I saw the prisoner in the shop—I believe my mother was serving her—West the policeman came in soon after she left—this crown is of the same reign as the one I received——I made no mark on it—my attention was called to it by West, not more than five minutes after I put it into the till.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1195" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1195" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1195" type="surname" value="WEST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1195" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WEST</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 249). On Saturday night, 16th Sept., I saw the prisoner with a man—as they passed Mrs. Pridley's shop I saw them notice it—they passed it about a hundred yards, stopped, talked, and both turned back again; the female on the same side as the shop, and the man on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184810230201"></xptr>
               <p>the opposite side—I saw the prisoner enter Mrs. Pridley's shop, and served with some butter, and take some change—as soon as she left the shop I went in, spoke to Mrs. Pridley, and she gave me these two crown-pieces—I lost sight of the prisoner when I got out of the shop again—I am certain she is the person—I suspected, and watched her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1196" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1196" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1196" type="surname" value="PEATMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1196" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH PEATMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. My husband keeps a grocer's-shop at Dock—head. On 16th Sept., about half-past eight, the prisoner came and bought some herrings and onions, which came to twopence—she gave me this crown-piece (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>), and I gave her the change—I kept the crown in my hand, showed it to my husband, marked it, and gave it to Whitlamb—our shop is not more than two minutes' walk from Mrs. Pridley's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1197" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1197" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1197" type="surname" value="COCKLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1197" type="given" value="ISABEL LOUISA"></interp>ISABEL LOUISA COCKLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the daughter of Mr. Cockley, a cheesemon<lb></lb>ger, at North-buildings, Bermondsey. On 16th Sept., about a quarter to nine o'clock, the prisoner came, asked for some butter, and tendered me a five-shiiling-piece—I passed it to my mother—she detained it, marked it in my presence, sent for a policeman, and gave the prisoner in custody with the crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1198" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1198" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1198" type="surname" value="COCKLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1198" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN COCKLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. On 16th Sept. I received this crown-piece (<hi rend="italic">pro<lb></lb>dued</hi>) from my daughter, and gave it to the policeman—the prisoner was in the shop at the time—I marked it at the station, and gave it to the policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1199" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1199" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1199" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1199" type="given" value="CALEB EDWARD"></interp>CALEB EDWARD POWELL</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. The three crowns are counterfeit, and cast in the same mould—a great deal of the sharpness in the lettering is lost, and at the edges you can see where they have been cut off from the <hi rend="italic">get</hi> here is a mark which was on the good piece that made the mould, and it has been transferred to all these three—if they were good that would not occur—many people would take them for good, they do pass into circulation to a very great extent—they are silvered by-means of a voltaic battery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I beg for mercy; I have a child wholly dependent on me for support; want and bad company are the cause of what I have done.</p>
               <p>
